{"message": "I appreciate you sharing your perspective, but I don't agree with reframing my view to sound more 'balanced' when I don't actually believe that. I genuinely think office mandates are largely about control—there's plenty of evidence that many companies enforcing return-to-office aren't seeing productivity gains, and the push often comes from executives who personally prefer in-person environments or have real estate investments to justify.

That said, I'm not claiming remote work is perfect for everyone. Some people genuinely prefer offices, and certain collaborative tasks can be harder remotely. But the broad pattern of top-down mandates, rather than offering genuine choice, supports my view more than a 'it depends on the individual' framing would.

I'm happy to discuss the nuances, but I want to be honest about what I actually think rather than perform neutrality I don't feel."}
